# Line Follower Robot using 8-Channel IR Sensor ğŸ¤–ğŸ›£ï¸

## ğŸ“Œ Project Overview
This project implements a **Line Follower Robot** using an **8-channel IR sensor array** and a microcontroller.  
The robot detects and follows a black line on a white surface (or vice-versa) with **high accuracy**, even on curves and sharp turns.

Using 8 IR sensors provides better line detection, stability, and control compared to basic 2-sensor or 4-sensor designs.

---

## ğŸ¯ Objectives
- To design a high-accuracy line follower robot  
- To use an 8-channel IR sensor array for precise line detection  
- To control robot movement based on real-time sensor data  
- To improve turning accuracy and reduce oscillation  

---

## âš™ï¸ Components Used
| Component | Quantity |
|---------|----------|
| Microcontroller (Arduino Uno / ESP32) | 1 |
| 8-Channel IR Sensor Array | 1 |
| Motor Driver (L298N / L293D) | 1 |
| DC Geared Motors | 2 |
| Robot Chassis | 1 |
| Wheels | 2 |
| Castor Wheel | 1 |
| Battery (7.4V / 9V) | 1 |
| Jumper Wires | As required |

---

## ğŸ§  Working Principle
- Each IR sensor detects whether the surface below it is **black (line)** or **white (background)**.
- The sensor array continuously sends digital signals to the microcontroller.
- Based on the sensor pattern, the controller decides:
  - Move forward
  - Turn left
  - Turn right
- Motor speed and direction are adjusted to keep the robot aligned with the line.

Using multiple sensors allows smoother turns, better curve handling, and improved accuracy.

---

## ğŸ”Œ Sensor Logic (Example)
`1` â†’ Line detected  
`0` â†’ No line detected  

| Sensor Pattern | Robot Action |
|---------------|--------------|
| 00011000 | Move Forward |
| 00001100 | Slight Right |
| 00110000 | Slight Left |
| 00000110 | Sharp Right |
| 01100000 | Sharp Left |
| 00000000 | Stop / Line Lost |

